'''Silvan Dominic Widmer''' (born 5 March 1993) is a Swiss professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[right-back]] for [[Bundesliga]] club [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]], whom he [[captain (association football)|captains]], and the [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland national team]].

==Club career==
Widmer began his playing career at SV Würenlos and [[FC Baden]] before he moved on to [[FC Aarau]] where he rose through their youth ranks, soon playing regularly for Aarau's reserve team. He eventually made his league debut on 23 July 2011 against [[FC Winterthur]], starting the match.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football.ch/sfl/777811/de/Teamaufgebot.aspx |title=FC Winterthur v. FC Aarau |work=Swiss Football League |publisher=Schweizerischer Fussballverband |access-date=15 April 2012 }}</ref> He scored his first [[Swiss Challenge League]] goal in a 2–2 home draw against [[FC St. Gallen]] on 21 November 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football.ch/sfl/777811/de/Teamaufgebot.aspx |title=FC Aarau v. FC St. Gallen |work=Swiss Football League |publisher=Schweizerischer Fussballverband |access-date=15 April 2012 }}</ref>

He signed with [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]] in the summer of 2012, but remained at Aarau for the 2012–13 season.

On 12 July 2018, Widmer signed with [[FC Basel|Basel]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/calcio-mercato/2018/07/12-45288555/calciomercato_udinese_ufficiale_ceduto_widmer_al_basilea/|title=Widmer signed with Basel|date=12 July 2018 |access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> for a club record €5.5 million.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|Kicker]]|page=209|title=Europas Top-Ligen 2018/2019}}</ref>

Under trainer [[Marcel Koller]], Basel won the [[2018–19 Swiss Cup|Swiss Cup in the 2018–19 season]]. In the first round Basel beat FC Montlingen 3–0, in the second round [[FC Echallens|Echallens Région]] 7–2 and in the round of 16 [[FC Winterthur|Winterthur]] 1–0. In the quarter-finals [[FC Sion|Sion]] were defeated 4–2 after extra time and in the semi-finals [[FC Zürich|Zürich]] were defeated 3–1. All these games were played away from home. The final was held on 19 May 2019 in the [[Stade de Suisse|Stade de Suisse Wankdorf Bern]] against [[FC Thun|Thun]]. Striker [[Albian Ajeti]] scored the first goal and [[Fabian Frei]] the second for Basel. [[Dejan Sorgić]] then netted a goal for Thun, but the end result was 2–1 for Basel.<ref name="fcb-achiv-fcb-thun-cupfinal-2018–19">{{cite web | last = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv” | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=31396 | title = FC Basel - FC Thun 2:1 (1:0) | publisher = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv” | access-date = 16 November 2019}}</ref> Widmer played in five cup games and scored one goal, the winning goal in the match against Winterthur.<ref name="fcb-achiv-winterthur-fcb-2018–19">{{cite web | last = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv” | url = https://www.fcb-archiv.ch/saison/spiele?command=detail&id=31384 | title = FC Winterthur - FC Basel 0:1 (0:0) | publisher = Verein "Basler Fussballarchiv” | access-date = 16 November 2019}}</ref>

Widmer moved to [[Bundesliga]] club [[1. FSV Mainz 05]] in July 2021, having agreed a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mainz 05 holt EM-Fahrer Silvan Widmer vom FC Basel |url=https://www.kicker.de/mainz-holt-em-fahrer-widmer-der-bringt-alles-mit-865018/artikel |website=kicker |access-date=9 July 2021 |language=de |date=9 July 2021}}</ref>

==International career==
Widmer was a Switzerland youth international having played both at [[Switzerland national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[Switzerland national under-21 football team|under-21]] level.

He made his debut for the [[Switzerland national football team|Swiss senior team]] as a 59th-minute substitute for [[Stephan Lichtsteiner]] in a [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying Group E|UEFA Euro 2016 qualifier]] against [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]] on 12 October 2014.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[UEFA]]|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/match/2013885--san-marino-vs-switzerland/|title=San Marino v Switzerland game report|date=14 October 2014}}</ref>

Widmer scored his first international goal for Switzerland on 6 September 2020, in a 1–1 [[2020–21 UEFA Nations League|UEFA Nations League]] draw against [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/news/0261-104ff2237dcd-4ef6a770f7ad-1000--switzerland-1-1-germany-widmer-thwarts-visitors|title= Switzerland 1–1 Germany: Widmer thwarts visitors |date=6 September 2020|access-date=16 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref>

He was a member of the Swiss squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020]],<ref>[https://www.uefa.com UEFA] / uefaeuro-2020 / match / 2024485 - switzerland-vs-spain / lineups /? iv = true</ref> where he made his tournament debut as a substitute in the second group match against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] on 16 June. He went on the start the final group match against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]], as well as in the round of 16 against [[France national football team|France]] and the quarter-final against [[Spain national football team|Spain]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/match/2017893--switzerland-vs-france/events/|title=Switzerland vs France – Events|date=28 June 2021|website=UEFA|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198650|title=Switzerland 1–1 Spain: Spain beat Switzerland on penalties to reach Euros semis|date=1 July 2021|website=BBC Sport|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref>

Widmer played in seven of Switzerland's eight [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] matches, scoring in the team's 1–1 draw with Italy on 14 November 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.blick.ch/sport/fussball/nati/einst-verschmaeht-jetzt-gefeiert-widmer-ist-ploetzlich-knipser-id16985118.html|title= WM-Qualifikation: Widmer lässt mit seinem Treffer die Schweiz träumen|language=German|date=14 November 2021|access-date=16 June 2024|website=Blick}}</ref>

At the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] finals in Qatar, Widmer started all three of Switzerland's [[2022 FIFA World Cup Group G|Group G]] matches, but was unavailable for the team's 6–1 loss to [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]] due to illness.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.tdg.ch/edimilson-fernandes-titulaire-contre-le-portugal-737559546034|title= Qatar 2022 Edimilson Fernandes titulaire contre le Portugal|language=French|date=6 December 2022|access-date=16 June 2024|website=Tribune de Genève}}</ref>

Widmer started all three of Switzerland's [[UEFA Euro 2024]] [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] matches at right wing-back and was yellow carded in both the 3–1 win against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] and the 1–1 draw with Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy99107knekt#Line-ups|title=Hungary 1–3 Switzerland LIVE: UEFA Euro 2024 – score, updates & reaction|website=BBC Sport|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref> He was suspended for the [[UEFA Euro 2024 knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]] match against Italy, which Switzerland won 2–0 to knock out the defending champions. In the quarter-final against [[England national football team|England]], he came on as a substitute for [[Ruben Vargas]] in the 64th minute and received his third yellow card of the tournament in the 85th minute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/teams/players/250042877--silvan-widmer/matches/|title=Silvan Widmer – Matches|access-date=10 July 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref>

